Department of Justice Law Enforcement Components EOUSA Data
Regarding Department of Justice law enforcement actions (e.g., number of investigations, arrests, and prosecutions), we obtained identity theftrelated statistics from the Executive Office for U.S. Attorneys (EOUSA) and the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI).
For fiscal years 1996 through 2000, EOUSA provided us with statistics on the number of cases filed under federal statutes related to identity fraud.
As indicated in table 8: The number of cases filed under 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1028 reflect year-to-year increases and more than doubled from 314 cases in 1996 to 775 cases in 2000.
Â· The number of cases filed under 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1029 reflect a general decrease, and the most recent figure--703 cases in 2000--is considerably lower than the 924 cases filed in 1996.
Â· The number of cases filed under 42 U.S.C. Â§ 408 reflect a general increase.
The number of cases filed increased substantially in 1998, when compared with the previous 2 years.
And, the number of cases filed in 2000 was more than double the number filed in 1996.
